			<div class="content" id="post-content-1590003">
									

<p>I thought the same thing, it would make a fine addition to the Imaginary Library, were it not for the anomalous 'extending' of the text.<br />
I thought it was sublimely written, but it does leave me wondering what's going on. I was sort of rooting for tales from the afterlife (or better yet, from Hell).</p>
<p>+1</p>
<p>One thing: in the the following paragraph, I think you could change the last fragment 'are related to the reader' somehow. It reads oddly after the extended parenthetical remark. Perhaps 'are described' or 'are delineated' or 'are conveyed'?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>As the narrative continues, events depicted in the autobiography vary increasingly from established understanding of Faulkner's life. In the closing chapters of the book, the narrator skips significant periods of time without explanation of events in between chapters, and events that appear to be completely unrelated to Faulkner's life (such as a stint as a water carrier in the Punjab, test-flying an experimental aircraft and being tried for murder) are related to the reader.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>One more thing&#8230;what about making the encrypted portion Faulkner's take on events after his death, as if he's still alive?</p>

