														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1589918">
									

<p>I'm personally shocked that any Lit Major could have any feelings about Faulkner that aren't positive! But I totally agree with you, besides that. This SCP just gives me a Lit Crit boner, and I cannot currently think of another that gave me one like this.</p>
<p>I love everything about this skip. Kalinin, it really feels like you have a good grasp of Faulkner's work, and that really strengthens this piece. I mean, jesus, there's miscegenation, weird ghostly females, and clear gothic themes. I know that doesn't really make or break the skip, but to someone who's familiar with Faulkner, that's just icing on the cake. The only thing to make this more Faulknerian would be if the burial rites conducted by the Native American woman weren't even correct for her tribe. (Speaking of this, if you could stomach trying to write like Faulkner, I think some sections of this would make a fucking stellar tale.)</p>
<p>As to the question of whether or not this is anomalous enough, I really would argue it is. I do agree with Cellar Door, however, that this is risky as hell. No one is dying in this skip. There's no monster, no radiation, no quantum mechanics, but I think it's all the stronger for it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
